Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Thursday! Hope you had a great long weekend and that your summer is o=
ff to an excellent start.=C2=A0
Not Boring=E2=80=99s mission is to make the world more optimistic. On that =
quest, we=E2=80=99ve written about everything from fusion [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/9665f377-1ada-4280-abe4-79bd898af0b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to AI-driven drug discovery [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/db8e2e1e-6c5b-4593-a23b-883275ce6951?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. These are bi=
g, bold, sexy bets that, if successful, will make the world a fundamentally=
 better place.=C2=A0
But sometimes, the solutions are simpler. Ezra, the subject of today=E2=80=
=99s piece, believes that early detection is the cure for cancer. It=E2=80=
=99s on its own mission to decrease the cost and increase the accessibility=
 of cancer screening in order to catch cancer early, when it=E2=80=99s easi=
er to treat. A world in which cancer no longer claims millions of lives ann=
ually would be a fundamentally better place.
Today=E2=80=99s essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive, and one of the ones I=E2=80=
=99m proudest to bring you in Not Boring=E2=80=99s history. In the spirit o=
f not writing about anything I wouldn=E2=80=99t do myself, I got screened a=
 few weeks ago, and I=E2=80=99m glad I did. You can read more about how I c=
hoose which companies to do deep dives on, and how I write them here [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/d340ede2-6e98-4646-9472-64515274b89a?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Ezra: The Quest to Kill Cancer
Let=E2=80=99s start in the future. Pick a year, say 2050.=C2=A0
In the year 2050, each time you step in front of the mirror in your bedroom=
, it runs a quick and dirty MRI on you. The MRI won=E2=80=99t be as high-re=
solution as something you would have gotten in a tube in 2023, but it doesn=
=E2=80=99t need to be. AI fills in the gaps and pulls signal from noise.=C2=
=A0
Most days =E2=80=93 99.9% of days =E2=80=93 you don=E2=80=99t even remember=
 you=E2=80=99re being scanned. There=E2=80=99s nothing to report, so your m=
irror reports nothing.=C2=A0
Very occasionally, though, it might notice enough of a change in your cells=
 that it recommends a higher-resolution, localized scan on, say, your prost=
ate, moves some things around on your calendar, books you an appointment, a=
nd summons your car to whisk you away to an imaging facility for a closer l=
ook.=C2=A0
The facility runs a prostate scan, AI flags the relevant parts, a radiologi=
st reads them, and a doctor tells you the three words that used to be among=
 the most devastating in any language: =E2=80=9CYou have cancer.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
They follow up, however, with words that have become commonplace: =E2=80=9C=
It=E2=80=99s very early, the earliest stages of Stage 1, and we can cut it =
out.=E2=80=9D Your car whisks you to a nearby facility where surgeons, arme=
d with a precise, 3D map of your tumor=E2=80=99s location in the prostate, =
snip it out before it has the chance to spread. Minutes later, a doctor del=
