Inducing Demand with AI
In April, I wrote a post called Intelligence Superabundance [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/d4bf5f4f-3353-4d09-b4d6-1b0edd800cef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] about induced demand and Je=
von=E2=80=99s Paradox =E2=80=93 related ideas that describe increases in de=
mand based on increases in supply and efficiency, respectively. Build more =
roads, get more traffic. Make more efficient steam engines, use more coal. =
I argued the same thing would happen for intelligence with the rise of AI.=
=C2=A0
Turns out, it=E2=80=99s already happening in cancer screening.=C2=A0
Later that week, I talked to Dr. Dan Sodickson, the Chief of Innovation in =
Radiology at NYU and Ezra=E2=80=99s Chief Scientist. Dr. Sodickson is a leg=
end in the imaging space. At the end of his Harvard/MIT MD/PhD program, he =
became fascinated with a question: why aren=E2=80=99t scans faster?
MRI scanners at the time were like fax machines, with a single detector gat=
hering one data point at a time in a slow scan of the body. Or, since Nvidi=
a is hot this week and we=E2=80=99re talking AI, they were like the data-ga=
thering equivalent of CPUs, powerful but single-threaded. What if you could=
 use multiple detectors at once and then triangulate your way to a complete=
 picture?=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s what Sodickson did, inventing parallel MRI, =E2=80=9Cthe use=
 of radiofrequency (RF) coil arrays to acquire MRI data in parallel rather =
than in a traditional sequential fashion, thereby enabling imaging at previ=
ously inaccessible speeds.=E2=80=9D Parallel MRI is like a GPU, a multi-thr=
eaded data gatherer. =E2=80=9CThe time savings are similar,=E2=80=9D Dr. So=
dickson told me when I floated the analogy, =E2=80=9CThe same is true wheth=
er you=E2=80=99re performing computations or gathering data.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Parallel MRI works because of computer algorithms. The scan actually genera=
tes less data than sequential MRIs, but can generate complete images by sti=
tching them together with algorithms.=C2=A0
Since then, Sodickson=E2=80=99s entire career has been a quest to answer th=
at original question =E2=80=93 why aren=E2=80=99t scans faster? =E2=80=93 u=
sing the best technology available, as evidenced by the breadth and volume =
of his publications over the past 27 years.=C2=A0
Sodickson=E2=80=99s mission, and the progress in much of biomedical imaging=
 during his career, has centered around doing more with less: generating hi=
gher-quality images with less data to go faster. That approach has four mai=
n benefits:=C2=A0
Raw Healthcare Costs. The quicker the scan, the lower the costs.=C2=A0
Patient Comfort. Patients appreciate being in the tube for less time.=C2=A0
Movement. People and their organs move, so faster means higher accuracy.
Accessibility. Faster and cheaper mean that more people can get screened.=
=C2=A0
Sodickson admitted that =E2=80=9CMRI right now isn=E2=80=99t the most acces=
sible of technologies,=E2=80=9D but he=E2=80=99s optimistic that AI can hel=
p. This is where we bring it back full circle to Intelligence Superabundanc=
e: he told me the piece I wrote described exactly what was happening in his=
 field.=C2=A0
The ideal state of screening would be to be able to screen everyone, regula=
rly, cheaply, and quickly, while minimizing false negatives and especially =
false positives, like in the 2050 scenario up top. That=E2=80=99s not the s=
tate of the world today for a number of reasons, which can be boiled down t=
o two: cost and capacity.=C2=A0
Cost. Historically, MRIs have been too expensive for most people unless ins=
urance foots the bill, which it typically doesn=E2=80=99t for preventative =
screening. That means fewer people screened, but it also means that even th=
e people who do get screened probably can=E2=80=99t get screened with a reg=
ular enough cadence to build up a longitudinal history, which would help ru=
le out many of the false positives identified in one-off exams.=C2=A0
Capacity. Say you=E2=80=99re able to lower the cost, or at least to convinc=
e insurance to cover it. Then, you have two problems with capacity. First, =
MRI tubes are big, expensive machines operated by skilled professionals. Mo=
re demand would overwhelm current MRI capacity. Second, radiologists are al=
so in high-demand, and more scans would mean more time reading scans (a sca=
n for each different body part may be read by a different radiologist in a =
process that can take hours) and writing up or dictating reports (can take =
90 minutes) .=C2=A0
Of course, over time, you could spend the money on more tubes and educate m=
ore radiologists, which would just increase cost. So it all comes down to c=
ost, and as Sodickson explained to me, cost is a function of scan time and =
radiologist time.=C2=A0
AI can help on both fronts. It can increase scan volume and help radiologis=
ts process the increased wave of scans. More efficient screening and readin=
g leads, Jevon=E2=80=99s Paradoxically, to more screening and reading.=C2=
=A0
Early warning scans, long a problematic holy grail in imaging, might finall=
y be practical. When I asked him why he teamed up with Ezra, Sodickson told=
 me, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d been reading the tea leaves in radiology, and see=
ing more things that would allow us to move to early warning. People were s=
tarting to work on more accessible machines and bring AI in to do triage. I=
 felt like it was time to rethink longitudinal monitoring.=E2=80=9D
Ezra currently uses AI in three main ways to induce longitudinal monitoring=
 demand:=C2=A0
Faster MRI Acquisition
AI-Assisted Radiology Reads
Report Creation=C2=A0
All three fit together =E2=80=93 faster, cheaper scans require better ways =
to handle the outputs =E2=80=93 so we=E2=80=99ll touch on each of them.=C2=
=A0
