Screening Out False Positives
While my test came up negative, the real danger with early screening is tha=
t it might turn up false positives, which can lead to high costs at best an=
d procedures that might do more harm than good, at worst.=C2=A0
I didn=E2=80=99t fully appreciate when I set out to write this piece that I=
 was wading into something of a war. Recently, for example, the US Preventi=
ve Services Task Force began recommending that all women begin mammography =
screening at age 40, down from age 50 previously, inciting backlash from th=
ose who believe that screening actually results in a net loss of life [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/bc8d4890-3e87-4a65-9d3d-c6ef84e987d7?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Nikhil=E2=80=99s piece, Why don=E2=80=99t we screen healthy people to catch=
 diseases early? [ https://substack.com/redirect/7bdb6c41-2c3c-47e4-b49c-d9=
80450abcd3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ], is a clear-eyed look at what=E2=80=99s become an almost religious iss=
ue.=C2=A0
I highly recommend that you read both Nikhil [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/7bdb6c41-2c3c-47e4-b49c-d980450abcd3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Emi [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe=
7da33c-3cd3-4548-955e-118b64703224?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=99s pieces to get a more complete pictur=
e of the false positive issue. Dr. Peter Attia gives a good breakdown here =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/eee7f129-1920-4146-9406-9eec5512bc8c?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], highlightin=
g traditional MRIs=E2=80=99 high sensitivity and low specificity, which may=
 mean that they=E2=80=99re good at not missing cancers, but come with a lot=
 of false positives. He also covers the fact that software is helping MRIs =
reduce false positive rates.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the approach Ezra is taking =E2=80=93 using software to redu=
ce false positive rates =E2=80=93 and pairing that with a protocol that min=
imizes the downsides of false positives when they do occur.=C2=A0
I asked Emi what they would have done if they had found something that look=
ed like cancer, and he told me that the next steps would likely have gone o=
ne of two ways:
Recommend that you monitor and return for a scan in a few months or a year.=
=C2=A0
Recommend a follow-up diagnostic scan that includes contrast to find out if=
 it=E2=80=99s malignant, which will rule disease in or out. If it=E2=80=99s=
 benign, they=E2=80=99ll recommend that you monitor it over time. If it=E2=
=80=99s malignant, only then will you undergo more invasive, and potentiall=
y harmful tests.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s one of the things that surprised me in my conversations with=
 Emi and Dan. Both said that in many cases, if they find a cancerous tumor =
in the prostate, for example, the recommendation may not be to immediately =
go under the knife, but to continue monitoring it. Often, what matters is t=
he rate of change, and not the existence of the tumor itself. If a client c=
omes back for another scan in six months and nothing has changed, Ezra and =
the medical professionals it works with may simply recommend continued moni=
toring.=C2=A0
Ideally, though, as was the case with my scan, the first screening won=E2=
=80=99t find anything at all, but will establish a baseline. The next time =
I get screened, Ezra=E2=80=99s AI can compare my new scans with the old one=
s to see if anything=E2=80=99s changed, and flag any changes, no matter how=
