t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Early success in software provided Emi with t=
he means to embark on his Good Quest: curing cancer. His Good Quest was als=
o a personal one, sharpened by two formative experiences.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">As a child, Emi developed hundreds of moles on his body, which put him at=
 risk for skin cancer and in the dermatologist&#8217;s office for annual ch=
eck-ups to screen for moles. He grew up living with the importance of regul=
ar screening.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Later, in 2015, a friend introduced =
him to </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6ff9fe0f-1bdd-4b3d-8=
6a5-a0a43cef7a91?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Hospice=
s of Hope</a><span>, a Romanian non-profit that builds and operates hospice=
s for terminally ill cancer patients. While skin cancer is visible and ther=
efore easy to screen for, his conversations with patients and their doctors=
 at Hospices of Hope helped him realize that &#8220;one of the biggest prob=
lems in cancer is the</span><strong> lack of a fast, accurate, affordable w=
ay to screen for cancer everywhere in the body</strong><span>.&#8221;</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">The question was how to solve that problem. Preventative can=
cer screens were expensive, often unpleasant, and potentially harmful, full=
 of needles, biopsies, and false positives.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #40=
4040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The an=
swer came in the form of a 2018 study that Emi read while noodling on poten=
tial solutions: </span><strong>MRI</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><span>In May 2018, a group of researchers published a study titled </span=
><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/5aa7a580-6a34-42f7-af09-24e85=
6dcb2d8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU"=
 rel style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">MRI-Targeted or =
Standard Biopsy for Prostate-Cancer Diagnosis</a></em><span> in </span><em>=
The New England Journal of Medicine</em><span>. I&#8217;ll let them explain=
 the issues with prostate screening at the time (emphasis mine):&#160;</spa=
n></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; =
padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Men with a clinical sus=
picion of prostate cancer on the basis of an elevated prostate-specific ant=
igen (PSA) level or an abnormal digital rectal examination are typically of=
fered a standard transrectal ultrasonography&#8211;guided biopsy of the pro=
state during which 10 to 12 cores are obtained. This approach is associated=
 with the </span><strong>underdetection of higher-grade (clinically signifi=
cant) prostate cancers</strong><span> and the </span><strong>overdetection =
of low-grade (clinically insignificant) cancers</strong><span>.&#160;</span=
></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9=
c797470-b321-4a00-af50-21c288e30ac8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: =
underline;">TechCrunch</a><span> described the standard method more colorfu=
lly: &#8220;Typically, prostate cancer screenings involve a blood test for =
prostate-specific antigen, with a </span><strong>needle-through-the-rectum =
biopsy</strong><span> done if PSA levels are elevated.&#8221; Not fun!&#160=
;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Fortunately, the NEJM study found that, &#8220;The us=
e of risk assessment with MRI before biopsy and MRI-targeted biopsy was sup=
erior to standard transrectal ultrasonography&#8211;guided biopsy in men at=
 clinical risk for prostate cancer who had not undergone biopsy previously.=
&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In English, doing an MRI scan before sticking a =
needle in the rectum was superior both at avoiding the needle altogether wh=
en it proved unnecessary and at guiding the needle when a biopsy was requir=
ed.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Emi read the study and in it discovered a path=
