1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Inducing Demand with AI</stro=
ng></h3><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In April, I wrote a post called </span><em><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d4bf5f4f-3353-4d09-b4d6-1b0edd800cef?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Intelligence Superabundanc=
e</a></em><span> about induced demand and Jevon&#8217;s Paradox &#8211; rel=
ated ideas that describe increases in demand based on increases in supply a=
nd efficiency, respectively. Build more roads, get more traffic. Make more =
efficient steam engines, use more coal. I argued the same thing would happe=
n for intelligence with the rise of AI.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: =
#404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Turns out=
, it&#8217;s already happening in cancer screening.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>Later that week, I talked to Dr. Dan Sodickson, the Chief of Innovation i=
n Radiology at NYU and Ezra&#8217;s Chief Scientist. Dr. Sodickson is a leg=
end in the imaging space. At the end of his Harvard/MIT MD/PhD program, he =
became fascinated with a question: </span><strong>why aren&#8217;t scans fa=
ster?</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">MRI scanners at the time were like fax machines=
, with a single detector gathering one data point at a time in a slow scan =
of the body. Or, since Nvidia is hot this week and we&#8217;re talking AI, =
they were like the data-gathering equivalent of CPUs, powerful but single-t=
hreaded. What if you could use multiple detectors at once and then triangul=
ate your way to a complete picture?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That&#8217;s w=
hat Sodickson did, inventing </span><strong>parallel MRI</strong><span>, &#=
8220;the use of radiofrequency (RF) coil arrays to acquire MRI data in para=
llel rather than in a traditional sequential fashion, thereby enabling imag=
ing at previously inaccessible speeds.&#8221; Parallel MRI is like a GPU, a=
 multi-threaded data gatherer. &#8220;The time savings are similar,&#8221; =
Dr. Sodickson told me when I floated the analogy, &#8220;The same is true w=
hether you&#8217;re performing computations or gathering data.&#8221;&#160;=
</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Parallel MRI works because of computer algorithm=
s. The scan actually generates </span><em>less </em><span>data than sequent=
ial MRIs, but can generate complete images by stitching them together with =
algorithms.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Since then, Sodickson&#8217;s entire =
career has been a quest to answer that original question &#8211; why aren&#=
8217;t scans faster? &#8211; using the best technology available, as eviden=
ced by the breadth and volume of his publications over the past 27 years.&#=
160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure style=3D"margin: 0 au=
