></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s the approach Ezra is ta=
king &#8211; using software to reduce false positive rates &#8211; and pair=
ing that with a protocol that minimizes the downsides of false positives wh=
en they do occur.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I asked Emi what they would have done =
if they had found something that looked like cancer, and he told me that th=
e next steps would likely have gone one of two ways:</p><ol style=3D"margin=
-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-s=
izing: border-box; color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Recommend that you monitor and=
 return for a scan in a few months or a year.&#160;</p></li><li style=3D"ma=
rgin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: #404040; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left=
: 4px;">Recommend a follow-up diagnostic scan that includes contrast to fin=
d out if it&#8217;s malignant, which will rule disease in or out. If it&#82=
17;s benign, they&#8217;ll recommend that you monitor it over time. If it&#=
8217;s malignant, only then will you undergo more invasive, and potentially=
 harmful tests.&#160;</p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s one of the things=
 that surprised me in my conversations with Emi and Dan. Both said that in =
many cases, if they find a cancerous tumor in the prostate, for example, th=
e recommendation may not be to immediately go under the knife, but to conti=
nue monitoring it. Often, what matters is the rate of change, and not the e=
xistence of the tumor itself. If a client comes back for another scan in si=
x months and nothing has changed, Ezra and the medical professionals it wor=
ks with may simply recommend continued monitoring.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>Ideally, though, as was the case with my scan, the first screening won&#82=
17;t find anything at all, but </span><em>will</em><span> establish a basel=
ine. The next time I get screened, Ezra&#8217;s AI can compare my new scans=
 with the old ones to see if anything&#8217;s changed, and flag any changes=
, no matter how small, to a radiologist for further review.&#160;</span></p=
><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s the goal here: to make scans cheap, easy, and acces=
sible enough that people begin to view them as a routine part of their medi=
cal care in order to build up a more accurate picture of what&#8217;s going=
 on in their body over time. That, according to Ezra, is the path to killin=
g cancer.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-ap=
pearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit=
-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appea=
rance: optimizelegibility; color: #404040; font-family: 'SF Compact Display=
', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial,=
 sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font=
-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625=
em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Killing Cancer</strong></h3><p style=3D"=
color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Sc=
reening isn&#8217;t the sexiest way to kill cancer.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Thro=
ughout the history of cancer treatment, macho would-be-cures like radical m=
astectomies, high-dose chemotherapies, autologous bone marrow transplants, =
and peripheral stem cell transplants have grabbed the lion&#8217;s share of=
 excitement and funding. At Not Boring, we&#8217;re certainly excited about=
 and investing in the next generation of potential cures, including immunot=
herapies.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The most important thing isn&#8217;t the novel=
ty or force of the cure, however, but whether or not it works.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">Writing this piece has made me confront a couple of things. My morta=
lity, for one. As importantly, though, it&#8217;s illuminated the fact that=
 the flashiest thing isn&#8217;t always the best thing. We all want a pill =
that we could take to protect ourselves from the devastating effects of can=
cer. That&#8217;s the kind of thing that we&#8217;d give top billing in the=
 Weekly Dose of Optimism. But until that pill arrives, spending time in an =
MRI machine might be the best medicine we have.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#82=
17;s not to say screening can&#8217;t be sexy and isn&#8217;t evolving quic=
kly.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Using AI to bring screening time down from 60 minut=
es to 30 minutes without sacrificing accuracy is a big step forward in conv=
enience and cost, and using AI to help radiologists read scans more quickly=
 and accurately will help them handle what is hopefully a deluge of screens=
=2E</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">And screening is only going to continue to improve from here=
=2E In my conversations with Dan and Em=
i, it really felt like the pace of imp=
rovements were picking up.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Emi described a coming shift:=
 from creating images sharp enough for radiologists to read, to creating im=
ages designed to deliver only the data that an AI would need to flag someth=
ing for further scanning.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Dan made a similar point, and =
one that&#8217;s interesting to think about in the context of AI more broad=
ly. Not only does AI change what we&#8217;re able to do with the data we ge=
t from our current machines, it changes the kinds of machines we need to bu=
ild and the type of data we need to gather in the first place.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">If the history of MRI to date has been a race to stronger and strong=
er magnets (the reigning champ is 7 Teslas), then the next leg is about how=
 small and portable we can make them without sacrificing results. He&#8217;=
s noticed a race to the bottom in the last few years, as imaging profession=
als have asked, &#8220;Can I make a 64 millitesla MRI?&#8221;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">That might lead to a world in which your bra monitors for breast cancer a=
nd your hat checks your brain. Maybe, sometime around 2050, the world I ima=
gined up top might be a reality.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">For its part, Ezra is c=
ontinuing to launch AIs that push MRIs down the cost curve. It hopes to dev=
elop a 15 minute scan that would cost around $500 in the next couple of yea=
rs, putting cancer screening on its own Moore&#8217;s Law-like curve.&#160;=
</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16p=
